        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You use functions of the certificate, key, and trust services API to manage and manipulate certificates. The API defines the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/seccertificateref"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " opaque type to hold certificate objects. You typically use such an object to indicate the certificate to use for a particular cryptographic operation, such as evaluating trust. How you get a certificate reference depends on where the certificate is stored or how itâ€™s provided to you. For example, it might come from any of the following:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "An identity."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " When you read an identity from a password-protected file or from the keychain (as described in "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/identities/importing_an_identity"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " and "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/identities/storing_an_identity_in_the_keychain"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": ", respectively), you can extract the certificate it contains (see "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/identities/parsing_an_identity"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "). In macOS, you can also store a certificate in an identity along with its associated private key (see "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/identities/creating_an_identity"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": ")."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "DER-encoded data."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " You can export a certificate as DER-encoded data that you then store on disk or send through the network. Similarly, you can restore a certificate from this kind of data. See "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/certificates/storing_a_der-encoded_x_509_certificate"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " for details."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "The keychain."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " Just as with keys and passwords, you can store a certificate in a keychain and later retrieve it from there. See "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/security/certificate_key_and_trust_services/certificates/storing_a_certificate_in_the_keychain"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " for details."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
